Mr. Bozyk - <br>
I have seen &quot;Vietnam - A television history&quot; several times.  It is a good series, and so is the book on which it is based.  However, it is not the only good history, as I am sure you are aware.  If you will excuse me, let me recommend Leslie Gelb's &quot;The Irony of Vietnam - the System Worked&quot; and of course Francis Fitzgerald's &quot;Fire in the Lake&quot;.  I believe you are mistaken to contend that OUR aim was to preserve colonialism.  We did want to keep the French in our camp, and so we wound up supporting THEIR &quot;colonial war&quot;.  It was our overall aim to &quot;contain communism&quot; which, in retrospect (Hey! there's a good title for a Book!), was a needless exercise.  However, it is only in retrospect that that becomes clear.  Yes, I still believe that the fight against communism back then was sincere.  I also think it was wrong, and I think we need to look VERY carefully at the history of our involvement to try and avoid similar mistakes in the future.  Failing complete avoidance, I'd hope we'd at least learn to cut our losses earlier.
